e right used.â Sheehanâs decision to abandon her role in the anti-war movement comes after Congress passed a bill that would continue funding for the war last week. âI think Sheehan was talking about a part of the peace movement that had faith in the Democrats,â said Zanne Joi, a Berkeley resident who is an activist with Code Pink, a womenâs peace organization. âThe Democrats had the responsibility to deny (the president) that money and they had a mandate from the people to deny him that money.â Joi said Sheehanâs decision is a loss to the anti-war cause, but that the peace movement will likely continue until the troops return from Iraq. âIt is a loss but it provides an opportunity for other people to step forward and occupy that vacuum,â Joi said. Sheehan wrote in the blog entry that she hopes to mend the relationships she has damaged and regain what she has lost back at home. âIâve been wondering why Iâm killing myself and wondering why the Democrats caved in to George Bush,â Sheehan told The Associated Press Tuesday. âIâm going home for a while to try and be normal.â Contact Vincent Quan at vquan@dailycal.org. Au Pair Nanny Agency (c) 2005 the Daily Californian
