http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-5&fd=R&url=http://www.allheadlinenews.com/articles/7007504765&cid=1116758582&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ AHN | Lake Okeechobee At Historic Low Levels, 12,000 Acre Fire 50-Percent Contained | news for the digital world Lake Okeechobee At Historic Low Levels, 12,000 Acre Fire 50-Percent Contained a.m. EST Linda Young - AHN Staff Writer Miami, FL (AHN) - Florida's drought has dropped water levels in Lake Okeechobee to their historic lowest levels since officials began keeping records in 1931. It had tied the old record of 8.97 feet above sea level early on Wednesday before a day of sun evaporated more water from the lake. Officials said they will measure water depth again sometime Thursday morning and announce the new record low level for the largest lake in the southern United States and the second largest fresh water lake in the nation. It is also the back up drinking water source for the 5 million people in South Florida. The lake should be around 13 feet above sea level this time of year. Dried vegetation on the lake bottom fueled a 12,000-acre fire on the lake around northern rim on Monday that was 50 percent contained on Wednesday. The drought has caused more water restrictions for the 5 million people who call South Florida home. Lake Okeechobee serves as the primary back up reservoir for Miami and the rest of the area during summer droughts. However, with lake levels at historic lows, officials have tightened water restrictions on South Florida residents, businesses and farms. In addition, four well fields have been shut down in South Florida to prevent salt-water intrusion. For the year, the region has been well below normal for rainfall with only seven inches of rain so far. ''There's nothing coming back in," Randy Smith, spokesman for the South Florida Water Management District, told the Miami Herald Wednesday. "There's just no recharge whatsoever.'' Although it is only the end of May, officials say that they doubt that the lake will receive enough rain during the remainder of 2007 to bring the lake up to safe levels so that it can used as a back up reservoir for 2008 either. Officials say that it could take years of above average rainfall to bring lake levels back up again. Copyright © AHN Media Corp - All rights reserved. Redistribution, republication. syndication, rewriting or broadcast is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AHN. © 2007 by AHN Media Corp.
