http://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/31/nyregion/31parade.html&cid Judge Decides Against a Mayor Who Banned Cuban Parade - New York Times Judge Decides Against a Mayor Who Banned Cuban Parade Sign In to E-Mail or Save This Published: CITY, May 30 &#151; The parade must go on. A Superior Court judge ruled here on Wednesday that the Cuban Parade of could not be prohibited from going through West New York, despite the contention of its mayor that the event did not do enough to recognize the plight of the Cuban people. The decision, by Judge Maurice J. Gallipoli, came two weeks after Mayor Silverio A. Vega of West New York denied a permit to organizers of the eighth annual parade, casting into disarray a festival that sponsors said would attract 350,000 onlookers. After the hearing, the parade&#8217;s founder and chief executive, Emilio Del Valle, said, &#8220;Obviously, I&#8217;m pleased.&#8221; Mr. Vega, who emigrated from when he was 10, had threatened to physically block the parade, which is Sunday, if it tried to come through his town. But he modified that stance on Wednesday. &#8220;I respect the decision of the judge,&#8221; Mr. Vega said after the hearing, adding that although he was not encouraging people to block the parade, they &#8220;might be inclined&#8221; to do so. Mr. Vega&#8217;s lawyer, Daniel E. Horgan, said he was not sure whether his client would appeal. The decision sent organizers scurrying to rearrange the route yet again. The parade typically travels south from North Bergen through Guttenberg, West New York and Union City. But when Mr. Vega denied the permit, organizers decided to limit the parade to Union City, shortening the route by about a mile. After the decision, Mr. Del Valle said he was not sure whether the parade would go through Guttenberg or North Bergen, although Mr. Vega said that according to his reading of the judge&#8217;s orders, it must travel along its original route. Critics of Mr. Vega said that he blocked the parade because he did not want to be seen with Brian P. Stack, the mayor of neighboring Union City, with whom he is engaged in a heated Democratic primary campaign for State Senate. The election will be held two days after the parade. In court, Mr. Horgan contended that the town was right to deny the permit because the organizers were a &#8220;fraud.&#8221; He said the organization, the Latin American Kiwanis Club, had misrepresented itself as a nonprofit group on its application, while operating as a profit-making group. But Elise Di Nardo, a lawyer for Mr. Del Valle, said that the status of the group was irrelevant in denying the permit, and that the issue should be whether the parade posed any &#8220;governmental interest or governmental concern,&#8221; on issues like traffic or crowds. Several times in the hearing, an obviously annoyed Judge Gallipoli referred to the proceedings as &#8220;nonsense,&#8221; saying finally, &#8220;I&#8217;m trying to make sense of nonsense.&#8221; Next Article in New York Region (5 of 24) &#x00bb; Need to know more? 50% off home delivery of The Times. To find reference information about the words used in this article, double-click on any word, phrase or name. A new window will open with a dictionary definition or encyclopedia entry. Saying Cuba's Pain Is Ignored, A Mayor Blocks a Cuban Parade Saying Cuba&#8217;s Pain Is Ignored, a Mayor Blocks a Cuban Parade Sinatra's Hometown Has a New Latin Flavor Salsa Fans Ache to Say Farewell to Their Queen, Celia Cruz Next Article in New York Region (5 of 24) &#x00bb; $15 million dollar homes in Florida, Wyoming and California Also in Real Estate: Explore the most luxurious homes in the U.S. Virgin Islands Explore the most luxurious homes in Hawaii Explore the most luxurious homes in France 50% off Times delivery. Jackie and Krushchev 1961 Home & Garden &#x00bb; Art & Design &#x00bb; Sarkozys: The French Kennedys? Phil Spectors Long and Winding Road The Dirty Water Underground An Animated Film by Jeff Scher Ar