 and that's where The Lede's mission begins. notes on the news "A directory of wonderful things" News blog and "editorial forum" of CBS News Your fix for education insights News diary from the journalists of the Guardian newspaper in Britain Focused on one important subject Updated by the People, for the People. News of the strange from Reuters News blogging from USA Today By Foreign Policy magazine. Supreme Court and legal analysis Covering the convergence of culture online and off Healthy scoops of tech-news blogging The New York Times national politics blog Politics in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut The cable TV news staple The "fair and balanced" network Global, Paris-based newspaper owned by The New York Times company Official "news" from North Korea News from Down Under The Los Angeles Times Breaking national and world news from the West Coast The Mail and Guardian Africa&#039;s first online newspaper (of London, that is) The Wall Street Journal Business and financial news National, international and political news, from the nation&#039;s capital The day&#039;s news in technicolor The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/7-3&fd=R&url=http://www.ksl.com/%3Fnid%3D148%26sid%3D1284243&cid=1116820950&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ ksl.com - On the Campaign Trail with Presidential Candidate Mitt Romney On the Campaign Trail with Presidential Candidate Mitt Romney May 30th, 2007 @ 12:05pm (KSL News) The "Today Show" was on the campaign trail with presidential candidate Mitt Romney this morning. "Today Show" co-host Matt Lauer spoke with Romney. And, of course religion was the topic of conversation. Lauer: You started your morning and you were at an event and a guy you were walking up to shake his hand. Basically said and I am paraphrasing here 'I'm one of these people who is not going to vote for a Mormon for president.' Are you worried that it is still an issue in 2007? Romney: Not really. I really don't think it is. I know that there are always issues that some people will separate from me on. But I don't give it a lot of thought. I am focused on the vision I have for the future. And the majority of Americans couldn't care less about what kind of church I go to. They care about what kind of president I would be. Lauer: But a recent survey found that 38 percent of white evangelical Protestants say they would have serious doubts about voting for a Mormon. Are you going to have to defend this faith or should you just come out with a Kennedy moment and say look folks here is the deal. Here is my faith. Here is what it is about. Here is what I stand for. Romney: Well, there may be well opportunities to do that. But whether and where I do that is a different question than whether the American people think there should be a religious test applied to somebody who is running for office. Lauer: You don't think there will be? Romney: I don't think there will be. Utah Senator Bob Bennett agrees with Romney. He told the Deseret Morning News he doesn't think Romney's faith will interfere with the outcome of the race because many Republicans like Romney's "family values." Bennett said they also like Romney because Republicans want a candidate who can beat Hillary Clinton. Bennett believes Romney is that guy, but says if Fred Thompson joins the race all that could change. It looks like it might happen. Thompson says he will form an exploratory committee next week. Ads by J Carter KSL Television & Radio, Salt Lake City UT EEO Public File Report A Division of Bonneville International m5 KSL's public inspection files, including the Children's Television Programming Reports, are available for viewing during regular office hours at the KSL Broadcast House.
http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ffile%3D/chronicle/archive/2007/05/31/BAGHHQ4EPA1.DTL%26type%3Dpolitics&cid CAMPAIGN 2008 / Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf / Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls" /> Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls John Wildermuth, Carla Marinucci, Chronicle Political Writers Thursday, hopefuls John Edwards and Rudy Giuliani plunged into colorful retail campaigning Wednesday in two widely different Bay Area venues, pitching two very different messages. Giuliani, the Republican former New York City mayor, flew into California for a couple of fundraisers, but took time out to shake hands and promote his candidacy to diners in Burlingame's Broadway retail district. Edwards, the Democratic former North Carolina senator, spent his day farther south, talking to a Silicon Valley crowd of about 1,000 at Google's Mountain View headquarters. Edwards talked about high-tech issues and the war in Iraq, but Giuliani was on the attack, chastising Democratic candidates Sens. Hillary Rodham Clinton and Barack Obama as tax-raising liberals who would cripple the state's economy. Giuliani painted himself as the only Republican candidate who is moderate enough to win a state like California in November 2008. Giuliani's comments Wednesday outside Burlingame's Broadway Grill highlighted the political schizophrenia he faces, trying to appeal to the conservative Republicans needed to win the GOP nomination and the moderate independent, Democratic and GOP voters he must attract to have a chance at the presidency in the general election. Giuliani, who supports abortion rights and aggressively backed tougher firearm regulations in New York City, argued he is "the one Republican candidate who has a legitimate chance to win California'' -- a state dominated by Democrats. Giuliani said Republicans must be able to compete in other Democratic strongholds such as Connecticut, New York and Oregon if they intend to keep the White House in 2008. But the former mayor also gave the party's conservative wing a bow when he slammed Clinton, a New York senator, and Obama, a senator from Illinois, as free-spending backers of big government "who don't seem to really understand how the private economy works.'' Obama's call Tuesday for a national health care plan is expensive support for socialized medicine, Giuliani said, while Clinton's plan to eliminate President Bush's tax cuts for the richest Americans would result in huge tax increases that "would hurt our economy. It would hurt this area traumatically.'' "We are the party of lower taxes and less government,'' Giuliani said. "They are the party of higher taxes and more government.'' Edwards' visit to Google came as he seeks to distinguish his message in the Democratic contest largely dominated thus far by Clinton and Obama. He touched on his plans for providing more Internet access and other tech-friendly issues, but appeared more eager to cement his identity as the toughest anti-war candidate among the leading Democrats. "I voted for the war, and it was a huge mistake and it was wrong, and I have a responsibility for that ... I'll have to live with that,'' he said. "The way the war in Iraq has been conducted has been a catastrophe for America. ... "The Congress has the power to stop this war ... the question is, do they have the backbone to stop it,'' he said in a thinly veiled slap at Clinton, Obama and the other Democratic candidates now in Congress. Edwards argued that Democrats in the House and Senate should have continued to send Bush war spending legislation tied to troop withdrawals rather than giving in after the president's veto. "This is life and death -- literally. ... We have a moral responsibility to those men and women,'' he said. Edwards continued to apologize when he was asked why he ever voted to authorize the war in Iraq. "I made the decision ... I did think the evidence was overwhelming about weapons of mass destruction, and I decided to defer to the president of the United States ... (but) I shouldn't have done it.'' It wasn't all tough talk. Edwards laughed when one questioner, Tom Zhang, a Google technology recruiter, made a reference to recent headlines about the candidate's expensive haircuts, saying "I like your haircut.'' "I wondered if I could get through this without that,'' Edwards said wryly. E-mail the writers at This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Sprawl clashes with warming in California Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Mo. Toddler Ruins Monks&#x27; Sand Design Gas station owner lowers price to $2.99 per gallon SAN FRANCISCO Officer called a &#x27;suspected&#x27; public danger New league looking to challenge the NFL SF Gate: Entertainment: Horoscope Bush Declares Self &#x27;Mega Decider&#x27; New documents ensure Dubya will rule... Digging biodynamic Restaurateurs look beyond organic in quest to cultivate... Dull, dull, dull, dull South S.F. transit village is a nothing in several... Whales disappear -- rescuers believe they&#x27;re back at sea Kids&#x27; rooms grow up Cute gives way to sophisticated designs, rooms that... PENINSULA / Stanford impostor also fooled people at Santa Clara University... SAN FRANCISCO / Youth mentor, dad of 3, shot dead in North Beach His... Bill would simplify changing names for partners, men Current law makes it... Pass it on -- Norris wants to keep Aces&#x27; legacy alive Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Putin: Missile Tests Are Response to US N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Listener Helps Save Ailing Disc Jockey Judge Will Release Letters in Libby Case The California Dept. of Corrections & Rehab. Work in beautiful El Dorado County EL DORADO IRRIGATION DISTRICT Systems & Senior Systems in San California Department of Corrections & Rehab. DESIGNER, Phil