http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-0&fd=R&url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ffile%3D/chronicle/archive/2007/05/31/BAGHHQ4EPA1.DTL%26type%3Dpolitics&cid=1116812583&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ CAMPAIGN 2008 / Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf / Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls" /> Giuliani, Edwards tread Bay Area turf Mountain View, Burlingame play host to 2 hopefuls John Wildermuth, Carla Marinucci, Chronicle Political Writers Thursday, hopefuls John Edwards and Rudy Giuliani plunged into colorful retail campaigning Wednesday in two widely different Bay Area venues, pitching two very different messages. Giuliani, the Republican former New York City mayor, flew into California for a couple of fundraisers, but took time out to shake hands and promote his candidacy to diners in Burlingame's Broadway retail district. Edwards, the Democratic former North Carolina senator, spent his day farther south, talking to a Silicon Valley crowd of about 1,000 at Google's Mountain View headquarters. Edwards talked about high-tech issues and the war in Iraq, but Giuliani was on the attack, chastising Democratic candidates Sens. Hillary Rodham Clinton and Barack Obama as tax-raising liberals who would cripple the state's economy. Giuliani painted himself as the only Republican candidate who is moderate enough to win a state like California in November 2008. Giuliani's comments Wednesday outside Burlingame's Broadway Grill highlighted the political schizophrenia he faces, trying to appeal to the conservative Republicans needed to win the GOP nomination and the moderate independent, Democratic and GOP voters he must attract to have a chance at the presidency in the general election. Giuliani, who supports abortion rights and aggressively backed tougher firearm regulations in New York City, argued he is "the one Republican candidate who has a legitimate chance to win California'' -- a state dominated by Democrats. Giuliani said Republicans must be able to compete in other Democratic strongholds such as Connecticut, New York and Oregon if they intend to keep the White House in 2008. But the former mayor also gave the party's conservative wing a bow when he slammed Clinton, a New York senator, and Obama, a senator from Illinois, as free-spending backers of big government "who don't seem to really understand how the private economy works.'' Obama's call Tuesday for a national health care plan is expensive support for socialized medicine, Giuliani said, while Clinton's plan to eliminate President Bush's tax cuts for the richest Americans would result in huge tax increases that "would hurt our economy. It would hurt this area traumatically.'' "We are the party of lower taxes and less government,'' Giuliani said. "They are the party of higher taxes and more government.'' Edwards' visit to Google came as he seeks to distinguish his message in the Democratic contest largely dominated thus far by Clinton and Obama. He touched on his plans for providing more Internet access and other tech-friendly issues, but appeared more eager to cement his identity as the toughest anti-war candidate among the leading Democrats. "I voted for the war, and it was a huge mistake and it was wrong, and I have a responsibility for that ... I'll have to live with that,'' he said. "The way the war in Iraq has been conducted has been a catastrophe for America. ... "The Congress has the power to stop this war ... the question is, do they have the backbone to stop it,'' he said in a thinly veiled slap at Clinton, Obama and the other Democratic candidates now in Congress. Edwards argued that Democrats in the House and Senate should have continued to send Bush war spending legislation tied to troop withdrawals rather than giving in after the president's veto. "This is life and death -- literally. ... We have a moral responsibility to those men and women,'' he said. Edwards continued to apologize when he was asked why he ever voted to authorize the war in Iraq. "I made the decision ... I did think the evidence was overwhelming about weapons of mass destruction, and I decided to defer to the president of the United States ... (but) I shouldn't have done it.'' It wasn't all tough talk. Edwards laughed when one questioner, Tom Zhang, a Google technology recruiter, made a reference to recent headlines about the candidate's expensive haircuts, saying "I like your haircut.'' "I wondered if I could get through this without that,'' Edwards said wryly. E-mail the writers at This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Sprawl clashes with warming in California Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Mo. Toddler Ruins Monks&#x27; Sand Design Gas station owner lowers price to $2.99 per gallon SAN FRANCISCO Officer called a &#x27;suspected&#x27; public danger New league looking to challenge the NFL SF Gate: Entertainment: Horoscope Bush Declares Self &#x27;Mega Decider&#x27; New documents ensure Dubya will rule... Digging biodynamic Restaurateurs look beyond organic in quest to cultivate... Dull, dull, dull, dull South S.F. transit village is a nothing in several... Whales disappear -- rescuers believe they&#x27;re back at sea Kids&#x27; rooms grow up Cute gives way to sophisticated designs, rooms that... PENINSULA / Stanford impostor also fooled people at Santa Clara University... SAN FRANCISCO / Youth mentor, dad of 3, shot dead in North Beach His... Bill would simplify changing names for partners, men Current law makes it... Pass it on -- Norris wants to keep Aces&#x27; legacy alive Man Described As a Top Spammer Arrested Putin: Missile Tests Are Response to US N.H. Governor Signs Civil Unions Law Listener Helps Save Ailing Disc Jockey Judge Will Release Letters in Libby Case S.F. Seafood Distributor needs National service co seeks Director of Production (San Sales Manager Will train