http://www.newsday.com/news/local/wire/newjersey/ny-bc-nj--cubanparadedisput0530may30,0,3229832.story%3Fcoll%3Dny-region-apnewjersey&cid Judge rules Cuban Day parade can pass through West New York - Newsday.com New York City News Judge rules Cuban Day parade can pass through West New York May 30, 2007, 5:57 PM EDT JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- A state Superior Court judge on Wednesday ruled that Sunday's Cuban Day Parade can march through West New York, reversing Mayor Silverio Vega's decision to deny a permit to organizers of the annual event. In his ruling, Judge Maurice J. Gallipoli rejected the argument of attorney Daniel Horgan, representing West New York, that parade organizers were running what amounted to "a charitable fraud" that claimed to use the parade to raise money for scholarships and other charities but actually were running a for-profit enterprise. Parade organizers and others had claimed the permit was denied for political reasons, and implied that Vega took the action to avoid having to walk alongside Union City Mayor Brian Stack in the parade. Vega and Stack are opposing one another for a state Senate seat in next Tuesday's primary. "It's been a tremendous ordeal through a mayor who was a little messed up in the head," Emilio Del Valle, the parade's founder, said after the ruling. Vega did not immediately respond to a telephone message seeking comment Wednesday. Attorney Elise DiNardo, representing Del Valle, contended that the denial of the permit amounted to a curtailment of First Amendment rights because it didn't reflect "any governmental purpose or concern" such as crowd control or safety. The parade has passed through West New York since its inception in 2000 and annually draws about 350,000 people. The controversy began two weeks ago when Vega announced he would deny the permit and said he would lie down in front of the marchers to keep them out. The towns of North Bergen and Guttenberg, which the parade also has traditionally passed through, subsequently did not issue permits as they waited for the dispute to be resolved. Attorneys for West New York claimed in court that the Latin American Kiwanis Club, which hosts the parade, was "misusing the Kiwanis name to operate a for-profit, sponsorship operation." The argument didn't sway Gallipoli. "There's a balance to be struck," the judge said. "Let the parade go on and report these people to the appropriate authorities and let them investigate it." Del Valle conceded that the Latin American Kiwanis Club had its charter revoked and would need to pay back dues to have it restored. "They were just doing this now because they have no leg to stand on after what their mayor said," Del Valle said, referring to the charges by Horgan. Subscribe to Newsday home delivery Article licensing and reprint options Post a comment |
http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/nationworld/orl-immigfees3007may30,0,4946538.story%3Fcoll%3Dorl-home-headlines&cid Immigrants face huge fee increases - Orlando Sentinel : Nation/World Immigrants face huge fee increases - Orlando Sentinel : Nation/World On Central Florida news At what point do you just let the idiots blow away? Hurricane supplies that qualify for tax breaks Trump Tower Tampa bites the dust Florida is in a serious funk How two years turned into $202 million at the Citrus Bowl! Public doesn't buy high college costs Summer reading: Are kids diving into books? Does the Newsweek top-schools list make sense? Third Grade Goof: Who's to blame? Third graders rule. Well, maybe, not: FCAT scores to be re-calculated Home invasion in Orlando Parents can voice concerns on crime in schools Kissimmee Police need assistance identifying suspect in early morning armed robbery Deltona man attacked during home invasion On local people in the news Hurricane Contest almost underway Stapp's wife: I'm NOT sorry for calling the cops Hotel taxes build roads ... elsewhere In Orange: Let the filing begin Readers on: Magic, evangelicals, Larry and more On Central Florida politics Jeb Sounds Like McCain on Immigration 'Numinous' too much for Ocala speller Ocala student survives to S-P-E-L-L again Democrats Want FCAT Probe Sen. Martinez coming to Lake tomorrow NASA managers to discuss Atlantis launch Dinner on the station: Canned octopus Clash of the titans Try a shuttle launch without leaving Earth Bill Oefelein leaving NASA Lawsuit: Wal-Mart shopper takes puke plunge When good hamsters go bad Don't tell your diet: Free Krispy Kreme doughnut June 1st! Regal gives moviegoers power to fight movie ruiners Share photos, find events, get news and join the conversation. See user photo galleries Send us your photos! Colonialtown / Audubon Park Downtown Orlando / Thornton Park North Orange / Ivanhoe Waterford Lakes / Avalon Park More news on the Web News from other Florida cities NEWS ON YOUR CELL Immigrants face huge fee increases Many say the costs are excessive for people who often are struggling to settle in the U.S. Victor Manuel Ramos | Posted May 30, 2007 Bush defends immigration plan Video: Learn more about the "Z" visa Chart: Immigration fees rising Immigrants applying for the right to live and work in the United States will pay a steeper price starting July 30. The fees that immigrants pay to request "green cards" will nearly triple to $930. The cost of renewing working permits jumps 89 percent to $340. And applying for citizenship will cost $595, an increase of $265. Some children will pay less and immigrants who fall under the federal poverty line can apply for waivers, but most others will have to cough up more cash. Immigration officials, who have hired staff and reallocated resources during the past year to reduce a years-long backlog to about six months, say the increases are necessary because the agency is solely funded by user fees. The increases will raise more than $2 billion, according to immigration officials. But immigrants and their advocates complain that these costs are excessive for people who often are struggling to settle here while helping relatives in their homelands. Under Secretary Emilio Gonzalez, head of U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services, unveiled the fee revisions in January, as the first major overhaul of immigration costs since 1998. The fees will become final after a public-comment period. Gonzalez said in a written statement that the new fees are "both fair to our customers and vital to our Nation as we continue to build a secure and efficient national immigration service." But some say the costs make citizenship less affordable. "This is ridiculous," said Gail Seeram, an Orlando immigration attorney who files applications for many West Indian clients in Central Florida. "These aren't filing fees. These are penalties. . . . If you examine any other government fee structure in the U.S., there is none with such unrealistic set of fees." Since higher fees were proposed earlier this year, many who qualified for citizenship but had not yet requested it rushed to submit their petitions. A recent Orlando Sentinel analysis of filings during the past few months showed that immigrants have filed citizenship applications in record numbers. At least 118,600 immigrants across the country requested citizenship in March, compared with about 74,200 in March 2006. In Florida, the number of citizenship applications was about 31,000 in the first quarter of 2007, an increase of 62 percent over the previous year. Applications for green cards, the documents that entitle immigrants to live and work here legally, also increased in Florida and the U.S. Miriam Vazquez, 37, a Dominican immigrant who works in a factory in east Orlando, was filling out her citizenship application Tuesday because she had heard buzz about the fee increase. Vazquez said that even at the current cost of about $400 for a citizenship application with fingerprinting and photos, she had to save for weeks to scrape the money together. "With the minimum wage we make in this state, it's too little money to pay for all that," Vazquez said. "I am trying to rush and do it now, because it's going to cost more." Richard Logue, who directs the Catholic Immigration and Refugee Services program of Catholic Charities in Orlando, said his office has seen more inquiries from immigrants. Especially burdened, he said, are those who need to file "adjustment of status" forms to request green cards. Those applications will go from $325 to $930, a 186 percent increase. Many who file that application also need to request a work permit, which will jump from $180 to $340 every year. Waivers of those fees, Logue said, are usually difficult to obtain for most immigrants. "Families had a difficult time coming up with the old fees in our experience," Logue said, "so some working-class families will perhaps have to forgo getting their papers and citizenship." Anne Yamasaki, 72, a German immigrant in Rockledge, is dependent on Social Security. She says she can't spare the extra $100 her green-card renewal will cost next year. She won't even think about applying for citizenship, even though she has lived in the U.S. for more than 40 years, because of the cost. But she also wants to see more-efficient service than she did during her last visit to the immigration office in south Orlando. "I live on a very limited income," Yamasaki said. "But it might be worth it, because last time I went to immigration I was standing in a little alleyway for hours." President Bush defends immigration reform. Page A9 Get home delivery - up to 50% off &copy; 2007 Orlando Sentinel Communications
