http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/9-5&fd=R&url=http://www.tothecenter.com/news.php%3Freadmore%3D1968&cid=1116323345&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ State House Rebellion - ToTheCenter May 31 2007 11:16:04 The Texas House was the site of angry protests this weekend. The anger over Republican House Speaker Tom Craddicks treatment of House rules has been brewing for some time. Early Monday morning, nearly 60 lawmakers walked out of the chamber after Craddick refused to allow a vote on whether he should remain the speaker. The walkout broke a quorum and forced the House to adjourn. This man is sitting here violating every rule of the House, every rule of parliamentary procedure to keep himself in office, and its wrong, said Rep. Pat Haggerty, R-El Paso. House Democratic leader Jim Dunnam of Waco said, Weve had enough. This was not the first objection to Craddicks leadership. In January, he won a challenge by fellow Republican Jim Pitts of Waxahachie. Alexis DeLee, a spokeswoman for Mr. Craddick, released a written statement criticizing the walkout as politics. Once again, some members chose to divert the House away from important matters and instead tried to drag the members into a speakers race while we are in session. The 140-day legislative session is scheduled through the end of the day on Monday. It appeared the Speaker had held onto his position as members returned to the chamber, after an appeal by Governor Perry to rise above their differences and finish the work of the people of Texas. Craddicks two-year term does not expire until the next legislative session convenes, in January 2009. Already, five Republicans have said they will be running against him. Whomever the next speaker turns out to be, they will most likely find that the House rules have been rewritten. Burt Solomons, the Chairman of the Financial Institution, and the person who carried House rules through its ratification in January, said it was never the intent of the rules to give the speaker absolute authority. He promised that the rules would be revised so that the next speaker would not be able to claim the amount of power Craddick has. Information from the Associated Press, Reuters, and the Dallas Morning News was used in this report. on May 28 2007 18:15:21 on May 28 2007 21:09:45 I am amused by this story, since the Republicans want to remove their own Speaker. I wonder, if it is not one man&#39;s failure to lead or indicative of other problems. Please Login to Post a Comment. Rating is available to Members only. Please login or register to vote. No Ratings have been Posted. Not a member yet? Request a new one
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://jurist.law.pitt.edu/paperchase/2007/05/doj-confirms-widened-internal-probe-on.php&cid=1116803877&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ JURIST - Paper Chase: DOJ confirms widened internal probe on politicized hiring decisions Serious law. Primary sources. Global perspective. Wednesday, May 30, 2007 DOJ confirms widened internal probe on politicized hiring decisions at 7:18 PM ET Office of Inspector General Office of Professional Responsibility [official websites] of the US Department of Justice (DOJ) have [JURIST report] into whether politics played a role in hiring decisions within the department, the DOJ confirmed in a [PDF text] sent Wednesday to the Senate Judiciary Committee. The announcement comes on the heels of last week's [JURIST report] from former DOJ aide [JURIST news archive] before the House Judiciary Committee on the controversial firings of US attorneys [JURIST news archive]. According to the letter, the DOJ's internal probe will now investigate allegations of improperly politicized hiring decisions of career employees, including members of its Honors Program, Summer Law Intern Program, and Civil Rights Division. Senate Judiciary Chairman Sen. Patrick Leahy (D-VT) [press release] the move as further means to probe the DOJ's "crisis of leadership" which allowed "unprecedented and improper reach of politics into the Departments professional ranks." Reuters has On May 23 testimony, Goodling contradicted March claims by Attorney General Alberto Gonzales [JURIST news archive] that he "was not involved in any discussions" about the firings. She testified that previous Senate Judiciary Committee testimony [JURIST report] by Deputy Attorney General Paul McNulty was "incomplete or inaccurate in a number of respects" and also admitted to considering applicants based on their politics in violation of federal law. In mid-June, the Senate will debate a resolution of no-confidence [JURIST report] in Gonzales, which ranking Republican Senate Judiciary Committee member Sen. Arlen Specter (R-PA) believes will be joined by a "sizable number" of Republican members of Congress For a one-stop snapshot of the latest legal news that matters, with breaking documents, new legal videos, live law-related webcasts, commentary by expert law professors and more - all updated through the day in real time, with no ads and no registration barriers - visit JURIST's and check back often... China demonstrators protest WWII compensation denials at Japanese embassy 9:23 AM ET, May 31 US immigration courts inconsistent in asylum cases: study 9:09 AM ET, May 31 Japan court upholds compensation denial for Korean WWII slave laborers 8:48 AM ET, May 31 DNA Evidence and the Death Penalty Holland & Knight LLP is JURIST's real-time legal news weblog, powered by a team of 20 law student reporters and editors led by law professor at the University of Pittsburgh School of Law. As an educational service, Paper Chase is dedicated to presenting important legal news and materials rapidly, objectively and intelligibly in an accessible, ad-free format. welcomes comments, tips and URLs from readers. E-mail us at
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-5&fd=R&url=http://www.courier-journal.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article%3FAID%3D/20070531/COLUMNISTS09/705310361&cid=1116617146&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ The past must be faced - and recognized for how recent it is U of L / Big East &raquo; U of L Fan Blog UK / SEC &raquo; IU / Big Ten &raquo; News of the Weird Send a letter to the editor Switch to EZ Pay Send us a photo Get morning headlines, breaking news, afternoon business updates, weekend happenings and more sent to your inbox! to join a discussion in our reader forums. Check out the new - Get the headlines you want delivered to your reader. View 7 days > Thursday, past must be faced - and recognized for how recent it is Twenty-five years ago, someone near and dear to me disappeared. Was he a victim of foul play? Did he bump his head and lose all memory? Or did he just decide to pursue new beginnings somewhere else, unburdened by a wife and a family? After a quarter of a century, I'm beginning to accept that I will never know what happened. Still, the last thing I want is for someone to say, "Forget about it. Move on!" I've moved on. But forget? Never. Most people, when someone close disappears or dies mysteriously, never get over it. Thomas Moore never got over his brother's murder in Mississippi in 1964, and he never stopped hoping that justice would rain down on those responsible. Earlier this year, James Ford Seale, 71, a Klansman, was indicted on federal kidnapping and conspiracy charges in connection with the murders of Charles Eddie Moore and Henry Hezekiah Dee. According to the FBI, the two 19-year-olds were hitchhiking in Mississippi when Klansmen picked them up and took them to the Homochitto National Forest. They were severely beaten, dumped into the trunk of a car and driven to Louisiana, where they were weighted down, thrown into the Mississippi River and left to drown. Seale was first arrested in November 1964, but the charges were eventually dropped, and the two young men's deaths were all but forgotten. "We didn't have money to solicit help from attorneys, so the old saying is, we just had to eat it up," Thomas Moore said in Kathy Lohr's "Morning Edition" report on National Public Radio this week. But while the taste of what Moore's family had to "eat" is bitter, he has gotten relief that others similarly positioned never have. He's lived to see this week the selection of jurors who may finally bring a scoundrel to justice. This case is one of many investigations reopened in the so-called Civil Rights Era Cold Case Initiative in which the U.S. Justice Department, modern Southern prosecutors and civil rights organizations are working together. The Southern Poverty Law Center, in fact, has compiled a list of more than 70 men and women who died between 1952 and 1968 "under circumstances suggesting they were the victims of racially motivated violence." The victims were tortured and killed in a variety of ways; they were shot, burned alive, hanged, beaten, strangled, castrated, mutilated, drowned or denied needed medical treatment. A civil rights activist recently remarked that with white supremacy being "the " in Mississippi, "to some people it was just sport to go out and harass and kill black people." Timothy B. Tyson, a white Southerner, would agree. Blood Done Sign My Name , the winner of this year's University of Louisville Grawemeyer Award in Religion wrote, "I don't know when I first became infected with white supremacy. But when I was no more than 6 years old, I discovered within myself both that monstrous lie and the moral cowardice necessary to its preservation." Ancient history? Hardly. Tyson was born in 1959. His book was inspired by the 1970 murder of Henry Marrow, a 23-year-old black veteran who was "killed in public as he lay on his back, helpless, begging for his life." And what burned Marrow's murder into Tyson's consciousness was a childhood friend saying to him, "Daddy and Roger and 'em shot 'em a nigger." "Many individuals have quite literally gotten away with murder," FBI Director Robert Mueller III has said. He warned those still alive, however, "We're still on your trail." This is a badly needed response to the people who live in what I call the honky-dory nation -- that place where everything is cool, where talk about unpleasant things simply is not allowed and where people say that no good comes from opening old wounds. All that comes from sweeping unpleasant incidents under the rug is a lumpy rug. Facing up to the past, including the bad, is the only way individuals and nations can heal. Betty Winston Bayé's columns appear Thursdays. Her e-mail address is I wasn't even born in 1960. What I see today FOR THE MOST PART is black and white people coexisting fairly and FOR THE MOST PART treating each other with respect. The last business dealing I had was with a mixed couple. That doesn't make for exciting journalism, though, does it? You can keep dwelling and bemoaning the items of injustice (for which this writer or your readers are not responsible) or you can realize it was a different time in this nation and be happy how far we have come in 45 years. How much more progress will come in the future? Do you want to be a part of that? Or, do you want to provide a reason for otherwise harmonious casual and personal relationships to feel strain because of something long ago we can't do anything about and had nothing to do with? Your paycheck must be more important than progress. Posted: Thu am Subscribe to the newspaper Copyright 2005 The Courier-Journal. Use of this site signifies your agreement to the Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Rights Send questions and comments to .Build 0: 16 ms (Misc)
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-4&fd=R&url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/nation_world/7760017.html&cid=1116803877&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Justice is widening its probe to other hirings | Inquirer | 05/31/2007 &#149; 2007 Live Career Fairs &#149; Philly.com Career Fair &#149; Search new & used &#149; Create a free ad , sports venues and more. See a photo you want? Photos of the day Beach and Bay Homes Active Adult 55+ Housing Thursday, on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Justice is widening its probe to other hirings WASHINGTON - An internal Justice Department investigation into the firing of eight federal prosecutors has broadened to examine whether the department used political considerations in hiring career employees for its Civil Rights Division. Glenn Fine, the department&#0039;s inspector general, and H. Marshall Jarrett, head of the Office of Professional Responsibility, told the House and Senate Judiciary Committees in a letter yesterday that the review also would focus on hiring for the department&#0039;s honors program for entry-level attorneys and on summer internships. The expansion followed the May 23 acknowledgment by the department&#0039;s former White House liaison, Monica Goodling, that she had "crossed the line" by inquiring into the party affiliations of people applying for nonpolitical jobs. Fine and Jarrett said they were looking at "allegations regarding Goodling&#0039;s and others&#0039; actions" in hiring and personnel decisions. The Justice Department began investigating in March to assess whether the U.S. attorneys had been fired for improper reasons, such as a way to meddle in cases, and whether department officials had misled Congress when testifying. Both Judiciary Committees are also probing the firings and the White House&#0039;s role in them. On May 2, the Justice Department disclosed that investigators also would probe whether Goodling had relied on improper political considerations in reviewing the applications of people seeking to become assistant U.S. attorneys. Last year&#0039;s firings touched off a political furor over Attorney General Alberto Gonzales&#0039; management of the department and his close ties to President Bush. Many Democrats and several Republicans have called for Gonzales&#0039; ouster, although Bush has repeatedly expressed support for him. Senate Judiciary Chairman Patrick J. Leahy (D., Vt.) said in a statement that he welcomed the expanded review. Goodling, who quit in April, told the House Judiciary Committee under a grant of limited immunity that she sometimes considered lawyers&#0039; political views when reviewing them for positions as immigration judges or assistant U.S. attorneys. Both jobs are covered by civil-service laws barring such assessments. Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST VIEWED IN THIS SECTION Russian says U.S. renewing arms race Obama offers health-care plan to widen access and cut costs Former senator exploring campaign Cindy Sheehan quits as activist Abdullah the Butcher takes a cut Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST VIEWED ON PHILLY.COM Time served, deportation for groping on a plane Eagles&#0039; Abiamiri a confident pick Two: Had drinks, woke being raped Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Updated 9:00 AM EDT MOST EMAILED ON PHILLY.COM N.J., with new agency, steps up fight against fat Monica Yant Kinney | Haddonfield teens going to extremes Boy Bags Hog Said Bigger Than 'Hogzilla' Stephen A. Smith | Bryant fires back at Lakers Teamsters still foaming over ejection by brewer Yuengling Latest Stories in this Section National bee tests spellers&#0039; &#0039;Bewusstseinslage&#0039; Kevorkian to leave prison, but not past, behind Former senator exploring campaign By Michael D. Shear and Dan Balz Marine tells hearing of civilian killings New Orleans stymied on high-rises U.S. to admit more refugees from Iraq Faulty repair, weak rules blamed in plane crash By Michael J. Sniffen Troops launch raid on Sadr C