 in Beverly Hills. Nick Bovis, the owner of the downtown Burlingame eatery, presented Giuliani with an autographed photo of New York Yankee legend Joe DiMaggio. "We want you to redecorate the White House," Bovis told him. He signed a copy of the U.S. Constitution for local campaign coordinator Vic Marani, 47, of Santa Cruz, and accepted a &#36;200 campaign contribution check from George Yerby, 67, of Hillsborough; Giuliani quipped it might have been "the first time I think one's been given directly to me." Yerby, who said he's semi-retired from real estate, said Giuliani's policies are "perfect for this area. ... He's going to be the next president." After a slow circuit of the restaurant, Giuliani, with a cup of coffee in hand, took a seat between regulars Mike DeMaria and Nicholas Fleres, both of whom described themselves as "New York Italians." The conversation ranged from the Yankees to California's early primary to immigration policy. On the latter, Giuliani said he doesn't support the plan drawn up by the Senate and Bush, in part because it doesn't include issuing tamper-proof ID cards or require a database of all foreigners entering and leaving the country. Bob Mayer, 56, a self-employed wholesaler from Millbrae, said he supports Giuliani for precisely this reason. "It's not a time to quibble over abortion or to quibble about gay marriage," Mayer said. Immigration, border security and homeland security are paramount, he said. "Everything else is just window-dressing." On the way to his waiting car, Giuliani kissed the forehead of 11-month-old Daniel Caruso of Burlingame, whose mother, Lindsay Caruso, 30, said they had been out for a walk and stopped to see what all the hubbub was about. "I don't know a ton about him at this point," she said of Giuliani. "But I'm interested, definitely, and learning more." Contact Josh Richman at jrichman@angnewspapers.com or (510) 208-6428. The Mercury News is pleased to let readers post comments about an article at the end o