 been filled with graduates of prestigious law schools, has been opened to applicants with mostly political credentials. Justice officials say the applicants are all reviewed by an outside committee before they are hired by the deputy attorney general's office. Democrats Patrick Leahy of Vermont and John Conyers of Michigan, chairmen of the Senate and House panels, respectively, said the allegations show the need for greater oversight at the Justice Department. Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., called anew for Attorney General Alberto Gonzales to resign. "As long as Mr. Gonzales remains attorney general, no internal probe is going to clear the air," Schumer said. View All Top Jobs A member of the Real Cities Network. Subscribe to the Newspaper . By using this site, you accept the terms of our Copyright 2001-2007 Cox Texas Newspapers, L.P. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-4&fd=R&url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breaking/story.asp%3Fj%3D14393400%26p%3Dy4393446%26n%3D14393488%26x%3D&cid=1116783089&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Irish Examiner> Breaking News> Sport > Bush tries to blunt criticism of immigration deal Bush tries to blunt criticism of immigration deal US President George Bush attacked opponents of an immigration deal today, suggesting they don't want to do whats right for America. The fundamental question is, will elected officials have the courage necessary to put a comprehensive immigration plan in place, Bush said against a backdrop of a huge American flag. He described his proposal, which has been accepted by a bipartisan group of senators, as one that makes it more likely we can enforce our border and at the same time uphold the great immigrant tradition of the United States of America. Bush spoke at the nations largest training centre for law enforcement. He chose the get-tough setting as a counter to conservative critics ferocious denunciation of a Senate proposal as being soft on people who break the law. Hoping to blunt that message, Bush emphasised that any new options for immigrants and foreign workers would not start until tougher security is in place. The presidential stop came during a congressional recess, with senators back home and facing pressure from both left and right on the immigration plan. © Thomas Crosbie Media 2007.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/05/30/bush_takes_aim_at_gop_critics_of_immigration_deal&cid=1116783089&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Bush takes aim at GOP critics of immigration deal - The Boston Globe Bush takes aim at GOP critics of immigration deal GLYNCO, Ga. -- President Bush lashed out at critics within his own party yesterday, accusing Republican opponents of distorting the immigration deal he negotiated with leading congressional Democrats and playing on the politics of fear to undermine public support. Bush takes aim at GOP critics of immigration deal Says conservatives use scare tactics, 'haven't read bill' President Bush's trip to Georgia opened a campaign intended to undercut the criticism that has consumed conservative talk shows and Internet sites, and educate the public. (Oscar Sosa/Bloomberg News) By Peter Baker, Washington Post | GLYNCO, Ga. -- President Bush lashed out at critics within his own party yesterday, accusing Republican opponents of distorting the immigration deal he negotiated with leading congressional Democrats and playing on the politics of fear to undermine public support. In harsh tones normally reserved for the liberal opposition, Bush said conservatives fighting the immigration proposal "haven't read the bill" and oppose it in some cases because "it might make somebody else look good." Their "empty political rhetoric," he said, threatens to thwart what he called the last, best chance to fix an immigration system that all sides agree is broken. "If you want to kill the bill, if you don't want to do what's right for America, you can pick out one little aspect out of it," he told thousands of trainees at a federal center here that prepares Border Patrol officers. "You can use it to frighten people. Or you can show leadership and solve this problem once and for all, so the people who wear the uniform in this crowd can do the job we expect them to do." The president's rhetoric underscored the bitter crossfire among Republicans over immigration and the enormous challenge Bush faces in trying to rally his party behind what may be the most significant domestic initiative left in his presidency. The White House has been pressing conservatives to fall in line, sending emissaries to meet with lawmakers and activists, but many on Capitol Hill and on the presidential campaign trail have ignored the administration's pleadings and rushed to denounce the deal. Although the proposal has the support of key Democrats, most notably Senator Edward Kennedy, a Massachusetts Democrat, the White House recognizes that its chances of pushing it through depend on winning enough Republican support. Bush's trip to Georgia opened a campaign intended to undercut the criticism that has consumed conservative talk shows and Internet sites, and educate the public about a complicated bill. But conservatives bristled at his remarks. "I don't think name-calling does any good at this point," said David Keene, chairman of the American Conservative Union. "What they've done from the very beginning is say, `This is the way we want it done and anyone who disagrees with us is outside the mainstream.' . . . It's been badly handled. They'll be lucky, given the attitudes in the country, to come up with anything." Brian Darling, an analyst at the Heritage Foundation, said he and his colleagues not only have read the bill but posted it on the think tank's website . "Most conservatives have very strong feelings that this bill contains amnesty . . . and no yelling and screaming by the administration is going to change our minds," he said. As for the charge of scare tactics, Darling said: "Honestly, I really think people should be frightened. This bill would be the most dramatic change to immigration law in 40 years and no one seems to understand what's in the bill. . . . The American people should be frightened by the closed-door process that was used and by the ramifications." The proposal would beef up enforcement with thousands more Border Patrol agents and hundreds of miles of more fencing along the line with Mexico. After that has been accomplished, in an estimated 18 months, the legislation would introduce a guest-worker program, allowing some immigrants into the country temporarily, and create a process providing many of the 12 million illegal immigrants already here a chance to earn legal residency if they pay back taxes and penalties, pass criminal background checks, and return first to their country of origin. &copy; Copyright 2007 Globe Newspaper Company. All Globe stories since 2003 are now FREE E-mail to a friend The New York Times Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-5&fd=R&url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/local/317850_bee31.html&cid=1116552892&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Auburn teen comes up dry in bid to win spelling bee Skip ads and navigation Thursday, updated 8:59 a.m. PT Auburn teen comes up dry in bid to win spelling bee 'Rambla' ends quest in national spelling contest WASHINGTON -- In a competition in which contestants proceed alphabetically by state, Jason Pu's burden in the 80th Scripps National Spelling Bee was to wait. Pu, an eighth-grader from Auburn, was No. 277 of 286 spellers in this year's bee, which forced him to wait on stage for 45 minutes during Round 2 and nearly two hours for round three while others faced the ultimate challenge in spelling. Pu made it to the third round Wednesday but tripped on the word "rambla," which means dry ravine. Pu, who admitted he wasn't familiar with the word, spelled it "rombla." The disappointing end was in direct contrast to his strong and confident performance earlier in the day. Despite waiting for nearly 100 spellers to finish in round two, Pu didn't waste any time when his name was called. He stepped to the microphone. He heard the word, asked for a definition then barely hesitated before correctly spelling "shindig." The success pushed him through to the third round of the nation's premier -- and most difficult -- spelling competition and a step closer to a grand prize of $35,000 cash, a $5,000 scholarship, a $2,500 savings bond and a complete set of reference works. He was in the third round with 106 other spellers, along with much tougher words and immense pressure. All 107 qualified by scoring high enough on a 25-word written test and spelling a word to a large audience. Pu admitted the wait was tough. "It's true. Because you're waiting for your turn and you don't really pay much attention to the other people, and then when it's your turn, you get really nervous," said Pu, who attends Federal Way Public Academy. He was sponsored by the Seattle P-I. In past years, spellers from Washington state have grown apprehensive as they watch competitors spell easy words. The fear, they have said, is that the quota of manageable words will end, leaving them with brutally difficult words. Pu had no such thoughts: "I like to think optimistically." Pu wasn't the only one who breezed through the early rounds only to fall in round three. The round eliminated 13 of the 107 who began. With more free time than expected, Pu said he will watch the bee, go sightseeing in Washington, D.C., and concentrate on one other goal. "I want to convince my sister to start spelling," he said. The oral round was hardly taxing for the top spellers. Tia Thomas, 12, of Coarsegold, Calif., back for her fourth national bee, correctly spelled "flagrant." The audience laughed when pronouncer Jacques Bailly defined "ninety" as "being one more than 89" for 13-year-old Mary Harrington of Vineyard Haven, Mass. Aishwarya Pastapur of Overland Park, Kan., made her feelings known by wearing a T-shirt with the words "mishpelt werds eeritate me." She displayed no irritation whatsoever when correctly spelling "enumerated." Kate Weir, 13, of Christchurch, New Zealand, traveled far to participate, and she must have thought the wait was even longer when she was kept at the microphone while the judges conferred over her Kiwi-accented spelling of "eeriness." Her spelling was eventually declared correct. The bee concludes Thursday night with the champion being crowned during a prime-time broadcast. This report includes information from The Associated Press. P-I Washington correspondent Charles Pope can be reached at 202-263-6461 or What do you think? Webtowns, your guide to Seattle neighborhoods, for more headlines and info from Add P-I Local headlines to Show of hands and more Don't start watching 'The Starter Wife' Read the Great Books by CASA Latina's unlikely ally -- Asian Americans 'Spam King' suspect seized Recent grads offer real-world 