http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-2&fd=R&url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/The_United_States/Immigration_law_foes_scare_Americans_Bush/articleshow/2085232.cms&cid=1116783089&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ Immigration law foes scare Americans: Bush-The United States-World-The Times of India Make TOI your home page Updated: 31 May, 2007 1734hrs IST | Immigration law foes scare Americans: Bush 30 May, 2007 l 0631 hrs IST GLYNCO (US): US President George W Bush has said that opponents of a landmark law to normalise the status of 12 million illegal immigrants were trying to stir up fear among Americans. In an energetic defence of the proposed law soon to be debated in the Senate, Bush rejected critics who are calling the legislation an amnesty for illegal immigrants, and said kicking them out of the country is "simply unrealistic." "If you want to scare the American people, what you say is, 'The bill's an amnesty bill.' "It's not an amnesty bill. That's empty political rhetoric trying to frighten our fellow citizens," Bush yesterday said in southern Georgia at a training centre for government security officials. "Amnesty is forgiveness for being here without any penalties," he said. "This bill is not an amnesty bill." "I'm deeply concerned about America losing its soul," Bush told the McClatchy newspaper chain in an interview. "Immigration has been the lifeblood of a lot of our country's history," Bush said. "I am worried that a backlash to newcomers would cause our country to lose its great capacity to assimilate newcomers," he told the news service. The bill, which was introduced in the Senate last week, could eventually allow most of the estimated 12 million undocumented workers in the United States to gain legal status, in the most sweeping immigration law reform in 21 years. Getting US citizenship will be a costly affair now Indo-US group voices concerns over Immigration Bill IT firms against Immigration Bill News in this Section UN expresses concern over Bhutanese refugees situation Indian junior wins US college title US to Bangladesh: Work within the framework of law White House shrugs off Castro's comments on Bush My Times , My Voice What is your resolution for World Environment Day? Should there be a cap on CEO salaries? Get the replica of your favourite edition of Times of India Feel at home.. Get the news on the move 4 GB pen drive Travel gear starting @ Copyright &#169; 2007 Times Internet Limited. All rights reserved. For reprint rights: This site is best viewed in 1024x768 resolution.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-2&fd=R&url=http://allafrica.com/stories/200705310003.html&cid=1116788973&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ allAfrica.com: Africa: Zoellick to Replace Wolfowitz As World Bank President (Page 1 of 2) Use our pull-down menus to find more stories São Tomé and Príncipe Asia, Australia, and Africa Latin America and Africa Middle East and Africa U.S., Canada and Africa Enter your search terms Africa: Zoellick to Replace Wolfowitz As World Bank President Posted to the web 31 May 2007 Robert Zoellick, a one time trade representative of the United States of America (USA) and former number two official at the State Department, was yesterday chosen by President George W Bush to be the next President of the World Bank. Zoellick, 53, will succeed Paul Wolfowitz who steps down by the end of next month, following a scandal in which he was found to have broken the rules in arranging a pay rise for his girl friend and bank employee, Shaha Riza. President Bush named Zoellick as World Bank President as indications emerged that the United States may be alarmed at the expanding military capability of the People&#39;s Republic of China and how it might be used, in a report released by the office of the Secretary of Defense. Although Bush announced his decision yesterday, Zoellick&#39;s selection must be approved by the Bank&#39;s 24-member board. Reports say the administration hopes the new nominee will receive acceptance from the board and other countries as well. In a statement, the White House extolled the qualities of its new nominee thus: "Bob Zoellick has had a long and distinguished career in diplomacy and development economics. "It has prepared him well for this new assignment. He is a committed internationalist. He has earned the trust and support of leaders from every region of the world." The statement further said Zoellick "is deeply devoted to the mission of the World Bank. He wants to help struggling nations defeat poverty, to grow their economies, and offer their people the hope of a better life. Bob Zoellick is deeply committed to this cause." In response, Zoellick said that it would "be an honor to help lead this key institution and to work with the many fine professionals from all over the world who are dedicated to overcoming poverty and creating opportunity." He thanked the President for the confidence placed in him. His words: "Thank you, Mr. President for the confidence you&#39;ve always placed in me, and for the strong support you&#39;ve continually offered. Your vision of public service is to strive for great goals, and with your help, I&#39;ll do my best." The executive directors of the poverty fighting institution had Tuesday outlined key qualities that are required of the next president to include a "track record of leadership, experience managing large, international organizations, a familiarity with the public sector and a willingness to tackle governance reform, a firm commitment to development, a commitment to and appreciation for multilateral cooperation and political objectivity and independence. While Zoellick&#39;s name was not mentioned by the Board, the statement however noted that "as the selection process gets underway, the Board expects an intensive process of formal and informal consultation with the Executive Directors on potential nominees, adding that "the Executive Director for the United States has informed them that the United States will be nominating a candidate." If he is approved, Zoellick will be faced with the daunting challenge of rebuilding trust and confidence in the World Bank, which had been eroded during the Wolfowitz saga. Worried by the reaction of stakeholders and international donors, the special panel that investigated the pay rise issue had urged the executive directors to consider whether Wolfowitz was fit to continue in his post as President, in the light of revelations that he broke the rules. Bush&#39;s new nominee has said he looks forward to working with the team of professionals at the Bank, to meet with contributors and borrowers as well as listen to different perspectives on how the Bank can achieve its goals. Zoellick also said that if his nomination is approved, he would work closely with the Bank&#39;s "dedicated and talented staff." During his tenure as US trade representative, Zoellick is reputed to have completed negotiations that brought China and Taiwan into the World Trade Organisation (WTO) in addition to enacting and completing Free Trade Agreements with Singapore, Morocco, Chile and Australia. His record also states that he completed FTAs with five nations of Central America and the Dominican Republic, as well as with Bahrain; worked with Congress to enact the Jordan FTA and the Vietnam Trade Agreement. International Organizations and Africa Under Bush&#39;s administration, Zoellick served with Secretary of State James A. Baker, III, as Under Secretary of State for Economic and Agricultural Affairs, as well as Counselor to the Department(Under Secretary rank). Meanwhile, in the summary of the report titled "Annual Report to Congress: Military Power of the People&#39;s Republic of China 2007," the office of the US Secretary of Defense notes that China is undergoing a military transformation and has the greatest potential to compete with the US. "China&#39;s ability to sustain military power at a distance, at present, remains limited but, as noted in the 2006 Quadrennial Defense Review Report, it has the greatest potential to compete militarily with the United States and field disruptive military technologies that could over time offset traditional US military advantages," says the report. Page 1 of 2 aggregates and indexes content from over 125 African news organizations , plus more than , who are responsible for their own reporting and views. Articles and commentaries that identify as the publisher are produced or commissioned by AllAfrica Make allAfrica.com your home page International Organizations and Africa Bush Launches New Funding Plan for HIV/Aids Aid Set to Drop, Warns Monitoring Group U.S. Trade Expert to Replace Wolfowitz at World Bank UK Premier Blair Pushes Partnerships President Bush Announces Five-Year, $30 Billion HIV/Aids Plan
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-2&fd=R&url=http://www.theolympian.com/news/story/121290.html&cid=1116693177&ei=muxeRqKEDZGoqwPX6vjNDQ 3 Fort Lewis soldiers killed; posts toll rises to 19 for May - News - The Olympian - Olympia, Washington Write a letter to the editor Notes from the ER Where do I take my Food & Drink Reviews Place a classified ad Published Fort Lewis soldiers killed; posts toll rises to 19 for May Three Fort Lewis soldiers are the posts latest casualties in Iraq, the Pentagon announced Wednesday, as the death toll for the month for soldiers assigned to the post rose to an unprecedented 19. The highest previous death toll in Iraq for Fort Lewis soldiers was nine in December 2004. Staff Sgt. Thomas M. McFall, 36, of Glendora, Calif., and Pfc. Junior Cedeno Sanchez, 20, of Miami, died Monday when an improvised explosive device went off near them during a foot patrol in Baghdad, the Pentagon said. Pfc. Charles B. Hester, 23, of Cataldo, Idaho, died two days earlier in Baghdad when the vehicle he was riding in struck another IED, the Pentagon said. McFall and Sanchez were infantrymen assigned to 1st Battalion, 38th Infantry Regiment of the 4th Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division (Stryker Brigade Combat Team). Hester was an infantryman assigned to the other Fort Lewis-based Stryker brigade serving in and around Baghdad, 3rd Brigade, 2nd Infantry Division. The two brigades represent about 8,000 soldiers serving in and around Baghdad who, along with other Army combat units and Iraqi security forces, are trying to rid the region of insurgents and quell sectarian violence. Command Sgt. Maj. Gerald Williams, who is serving on an interim basis as the posts senior noncommissioned officer, said losing a soldier never is easy, and the Army post grieves with news of each death. The soldiers commitment to continue the fight hasnt wavered and morale remains high, he added. We stand together with each other to make a difference every day, Williams said. McFall joined the Army in October 1994 and served tours in South Korea and Afghanistan. He reported to Fort Lewis for a second time in September 2005. His wife, Emily, said her husband loved listening to classic rock and cooking ribs on the grill. He would tell peers leaving the military that the Army was the easiest job in the world, she said. He loved the brotherhood and his heart beat red, white and blue; there was only one exit, Emily McFall said. Hester and Sanchez were serving in their first combat deployments. Hester enlisted in May 2004 and arrived at Fort Lewis that September, and Sanchez joined Nov. 9, 2005, and came to the Army post in June 2006. Family members for both soldiers couldnt be reached for comment. Today, Fort Lewis will hold a memorial service for Sgt. Iosiwo Uruo, a 27-year-old native of Guam, who died May 24 when his unit came under enemy fire. His will be among the final individual memorial services for soldiers at Fort Lewis. In a May 22 memo obtained by United for Peace Pierce County, Brig. Gen. William Troy, Fort Lewis acting commanding general, wrote that the number of fallen soldiers prevents post officials from conducting individual services. He directed the posts senior chaplain to draft a policy set to take effect next month. Fort Lewis plans to hold a memorial service once a month for its fallen soldiers. The details are still being worked out, Fort Lewis spokesman Joe Piek said. He noted that four services typically are held to honor a fallen soldier. The soldiers unit holds one in theater; a second at the Army post for the greater community that family members sometimes attend; the third organized by family in the soldiers hometown; and the fourth a burial with military honors. Christian Hill covers the city of Lacey and military for The Olympian. He can be reached at 360-754-5427 or chill@theolympian.com. Join the Reader Network Do you want The Olympian to keep you in mind when we canvass the community for opinions? C